    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2d362c30_cfef3e2f",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1147264
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-03T01:32:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The intent is to decouple SinkServer from rdb-stream as much as possible.\n\nThe definitions and usages of the fields in sinkStats{} are biased to `rdb stream`. sinkStats{} assume that the stat numbers of a sink run should be small enough to be sotred in int64 and uint32 vars. Also, it assumes that it\u0027s for a single test run.\n\nLet\u0027s say that a sink package was used in a long-running daemonized process with sink.NewServer(). It would have to implement an own EventListener, as the field defs of sinkStats{} wouldn\u0027t be suitable, especially those tracking total number and latencies of req/art/tr reported.\n\nI can understand that EventListener seems to be a premature generalization, if we assume that rdb-stream will remain the only application spawning SinkServer{}. Yes, I bet that it\u0027s going to be probably true. However, the APIs under sink package pretend that it\u0027s generic for general use cases, and doesn\u0027t limit its usages to rdb-stream only. If it\u0027s only for rdb-stream, it wouldn\u0027t have to expose any of sink.NewServer(), sink.Start(), sink.Err(), etc..\n\nDefining this interface didn\u0027t increase the complexity of the code included in this CL. Even if I remove this interface, I\u0027d simply relocate sink_stats.go to sink package. This would need a module to define the storage and logic to retain the collected.",
      "parentUuid": "c5693704_796008d1",
      "revId": "685ae912a3f4371c3dfa2fd9ea5292076d78864d",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "77ad7217_89d9b7ae",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-03T02:05:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "defining an interface is a significant increase of API surface and liability. It adds a new layer of indirection, which I don\u0027t see as necessary.\n\nre int32 vs uint32. Is the argument that saving 32*3\u003d96 bits justifies creating a layer of indirection? I am sorry, but I disagree.\n\nI think if the CL is scoped down only to things that are needed permanently, it will turn out that any host of SinkServer will need this. Specifically, Ben\u0027s point is that if we are closing SinkServer, but it is still doing something, any host (not only rdb-stream) would want SinkServer to report what it is waiting for. That problem is generic.",
      "parentUuid": "2d362c30_cfef3e2f",
      "revId": "685ae912a3f4371c3dfa2fd9ea5292076d78864d",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
